V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The originally carefree journey is made by a series of completely avoidable, dilettant errors to the routine journey to the early layer.
Although it was possible to fulfill the ambitions to a large extent, what good is it if obviously no one wanted to do a little more.
Even before he came to the barn tables, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
He promised to re-move the already-eldered game series "Need for Speed" into a new dimension, and in the playable demonstrations, he did not seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious as to how the passages that were fit into place, in which the main protagonist climbs out of the car and continues on foot.
But how you get used to it at NFS is very different in the end effect than you expected.
Sure - potentially there are pretty decent arcade races, but overall the game is reduced by some superfluous errors that are present in this series for more or less a few years.
So it's actually no longer a mistake, but rather a sign of a basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure begins very well.
For the first time, one is introduced into history, whose main character Jack has certain problems of personal character; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, that is, on the west coast, you get on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea contains a number of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and into more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is performed on a different route and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
One has no moment the impression that game would offer the same again and again.
Some environments are still very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the previous parts of the series.
So nothing moving around the world.
But the journey through the desert, through autumn landscape or high up through deep snowy landscape seemed visually very pleasant.
Over and over, untypical elements bring a little variation into the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm that greatly limits the view.
In the mountains again you must be careful that you are not wasted by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are quite well installed in a row.
Although only a few, but they're enough.
For a while you try to overtake the required number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then you expect another personal duel with a single opponent.
And that's what the police are trying to mess up the whole thing.
A novelty is passages where Jack leaves the car.
This is more about certain interactive animations in which Jack flees from someone and where the player needs to help him by pressing the right button at the right time.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far less such passages in the game than one would expect (in concrete terms only three).
In the end, this is more beneficial because at least this element has no chance of becoming boring - it is in the context of the above mentioned elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model steps into the footsteps of the previous parts.
In other words, from today's point of view, it does not rip out trees, but on the other hand one could not claim that it would be bad.
Anyone looking for realistic simulations has to look elsewhere.
But an action-loaded race will continue to be quite justifiable, although you could find better in competition.
Until then, everything is in good order.
Real problems only appear after some time.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not quite O.K.
A game of this kind can hardly be expected to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no impact on any object knowing how the car behaves, then obviously not everything is all right.
Typical example: When you overtake or overtake cars that are arriving, you "strip" the other cars easily in some places, but in other, almost identical situations you get into the sleuding and twisting wild pirouettes.
Or take the car straight to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn't matter anymore, but it's always annoying.
The restarts are solved this way: if you have total damage or you land far away from the track, then you throw the game back to the last stop of the track.
Only - in every race you only have five restarts.
Once you've exhausted it, it'll all start from the front.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something doesn't work, but you better not rely on them.
Sometimes, however, the restart doesn't even help, as nothing helps but to learn the critical section from the head.
Very unpleasant is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, you have to go through some curves in a very specific way, otherwise you just don't fit through.
Otherwise, you always meet "civil" cars in the same configuration at the appropriate location, whether you are coming first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations when one sees that the opponent comes by in front of a playful two arriving cars, but until one arrives there, the cars are already in such a position that one has to bypass them or brake them.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, because everything is so designed that it always comes close to this situation in front of your nose.
Contractors have other advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken at the same place by the same opponent and here again without regard to the time.
At the craziest, this is at the end of the game on the long bridge that one happens in the opposite direction.
The contrahent must obviously overtake one of these devils.
And then if he's already in front of you, he'll take a look, of course, so you can start by driving your own car a couple of times.
Of course - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting but this intention is so clear that it quickly misses you the joy at the game.
And that's a shame, because despite a simpler driving model, the game as a whole is quite entertaining and sometimes even so loaded up for action that you almost don't know where one of the heads is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what "guilt" is about - the concept of fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that can't cause boredom, or something else...
An unusual idea is also the change of car during the race.
You can't ignore the gas stations on the track, because right here you can change the car, although in most cases the car you have just got is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for the technical rides, for example on the Serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of the game history also goes the task mode (challenges) - i.e. the races in the individual locations known from history.
There are not only medals here, but also experience points for your own profile, which is common to the tasks (challenges) and history.
To get to a higher driver level, different items have to be unlocked: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is at the same time connected to the online Autolog function, which compares, among other things, its own achieved results with those of other players and also provides for further collective functions.
One of other incomprehensible carpenters is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you come by car to a subway tunnel (roadway), where you rest on the rails in the dark for a long time (roadway).
On the Tacho look at numbers between 150 a 200 km/h (roadways), but there comes a subway from behind and drives a uncompromising to scrap.
In our editorial team we will probably continue to argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the visual overall impression is in most cases quite appealing and even brilliant here and there.
It is all the more annoying that at some exciting moments the frequency of images is slowing down and sometimes quite dramatic.
This, however, is particularly true of accidents involving a larger number of participants, where a continuous FPS does not benefit anyway.
The sound reproduction is as far as OK and the soundtrack is tasteful.
In an effort to address a young audience as wide as possible, a soundtrack a lay "of everyone something" was created - but who buys such a game because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are rather mixed.
If the game were not thwarted by the mentioned totally unnecessary mistakes, we could have argued with the chest tone of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that's how the game works.
In itself a great pleasure, but one should be prepared to put these faults in the eye with the power of airport lights.
