IBM history: From cheese cutter to all-world flights
Founded one hundred years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM took over only 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation of the later company IBM laid the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They had technologies such as the famous card sequences to register the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint, who was also chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930, became the architect of this new company.
And it was Flint who hired the head of Thomas J. Watson's competition firm to help him manage the company.
This leader then even put the founders of IBM in the shade - based on Watson's ideas to this day the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson managed the company until 1952.
IBM, as already the name reveals, began with the production and distribution of all possible machines for trade - from sausage and cheese cutters to cashier.
In the first four decades of leading the company, Watson doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the chair for forty years, only then he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped manage NASA flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the series IBM System/360.
A classic PC that set the computer standard of that time came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus entered the business of consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off in the last three years is the concept of "Smarter Planet".
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even planned to date, such as improving the situation in transport and urban management.
In the commercial sector, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform to help retailers lead the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
In 1932 IBM founded a branch in Czechoslovakia - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
Central and Eastern Europe headquarters are located in Prague and there is also a world-wide top team of researchers dealing with voice recognition technology.
