Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five approved state travel agencies in the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
At the time, the travel agencies sold only travel to the socialist Eastern bloc countries, and in the West they were only allowed to select.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimea Peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that even the citizens of the Eastern bloc (also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies offered to travel to the west, but then they had to buy huge snakes or also stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel office.
This was not the case for a long time.
The so-called foreign exchange promise - the condition for an exit to the West - was granted only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that continues to this day.
The 1989 Joint Revolution followed a revolution of the Czechs on their feet.
While a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their vacation abroad in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, which is no longer known today, is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia by 1989 at all because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
From the beginning of the 1990s, foreign exchange obligations were lifted in neighbouring Western European countries, resulting in a huge wave of short visits mainly to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians could not get enough for a long time from their travels to the West, everyone wanted to be there for at least a few days.
Thus the Czech holidaymakers slept in the park when traveling to Paris in the tent, because at the time who had already had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a pension.
A typical feature of Czech travel abroad was at that time a boxroom filled with canned, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of living and therefore the average salaries increased, which meant 1997 at another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to regularly prepare journeys through charter flights after 1997, making the flights incredibly cheaper, thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already had currencyless payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-sammen" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand the first direct charter flight was completed in an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying in far-off sunny countries every year; this year, twelve exotic destinations are being flown directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 Czechs travel every year to exotic countries!
Another important moment in the era that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which made our country definitely among the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent for the first time more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 thousand CZK per head for a single holiday stay, including the cost at the resort.
