Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York Congressman Anthony Weidner made himself a fool of himself when he circulated denials that were very quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
The former presidential candidate John Edwards is charged with the violation of campaign financing, which is linked to the custody of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered when he lied during his second term in the Oval Office regarding his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories about school rumblings and college exams are widespread.
There were incidents in which teachers gave their students the examination answers so that they could do well even in their performance reviews.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and rumblings are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
As studies prove, we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
Many of these lies, however, are considered emergency lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Identifying lies or "discovering lies" is one that is important for every human being, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game such as Sharaden, in which it is the goal to call "Hab you!", deterring a deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at respected universities that carried out far-reaching research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of research is that most old myths have been deflected from the lie.
Lies look into your eyes.
They stutter, stammer, redden and don't always gag.
But we must not conclude from this that these liars are difficult to uncover and defile.
A trained lie deterrent can penetrate to the truth by learning something about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, about questioning and timing.
I have spent several years investigating the scientific results of the comprehensive and constantly growing field of detachment. And it is clear that detachment of a deception is a modern ability that is easy to learn and helps us in finding out in our complex world, especially if hiring or questioning persons or negotiations or administration are one of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at appraising other people's interests and controlling their own emotions, and they feel intuitive as they are perceived by others.
Thanks to the research, we know that the extroverted people lie more often than introverted people that men are more often "self-oriented" lies than women whose lies are more "orientated to others" - usually they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie to their partners less often than unwed people (but the lies they tell are mostly "fat lies").
We also know that when a person has been defunct as an evildoer, others feel less guilty of having lied to that person.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
This is called "baselining", the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the subsequent evaluation of changes.
Watch the attitude, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
You should know better when someone usually constantly triples with his foot, so that they do not wrongly accuse him when he triples his foot during a meeting.
Then watch out for accumulations of conspicuous verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Consider these accumulations as alarm bells that shrill, not as evidence of detonation.
People who deceive may stare when they try to remember their story. Perhaps their feet are pointing towards the door or they are leaning toward the exit, changing their position significantly or showing a "relaxment after the interview", this deep, relaxing exhale and the change in attitude when all the hard questions are over.
Askers often falsely signal that a job interview is over, only to look out for this relaxation after the interview.
Also be aware of the language of your subject.
Scott Peterson's snitch is famous when he used the form of the past when he claimed that his dead wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Deceptive people can also use a distancing language: "I had no sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if you repeat a tricky question in general.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when they answer a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth ... as far as I am known ... to best knowledge and conscience."
This makes the answer more perceptive than factual, often causing the alarm bells to shrill.
There is no means of magic to detear lies, but you can learn skills through which detearment is possible.
Thanks to these skills, everyone can become less likely to be the victim of fraud, both in private and professional life.
