Climate change slowed the economy
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and undeclared work rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment fell and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloas. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of change and gave great hope to economic growth, is in government. However, due to the climatic hardships, growth cannot be the talk of growth, but, on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses in agriculture at millions but also limited the growth of the national economy and in the first quarter caused a general fall in economic activity of 3.6 per cent. This is mainly due to the historical decline of agricultural development by 31.16 per cent, which slowed down on other sectors of the economy.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (the Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the effects of the frost, 582,000 hectares of land used for agriculture were damaged, 78.03 percent of which were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially destroyed.
The fall in economic activity by November has steadily increased unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, as from January to March, 55,053 inhabitants of Sinaloas had no employment, corresponding to 4.53 percent of the labour force. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent and from July to 6.19 percent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa, which is 18,969 people more than in the first quarter.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa this year is due to several factors. Economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented that public institutions' policies indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently observing is an increase in unemployment, which has several factors to do with. Among other things, with market liquidity losses as a result of the austerity cuts by the legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who are not allowed to accumulate dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or otherwise use them."
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment also has a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has decreased. This is due to the entry problems and, on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work there as well. These people stay here and are looking for work to increase unemployment," he says.
Blackworking
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if the high proportion of undeclared work is taken into account.
Unemployment and undeclared work are the lowest wages in all of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretary of Trabajo y Previsión Social (government Office for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of employees in Sinaloa was up to September 5352 pesos; that is much less than the general government average, which is 7375 pesos.
Decrease in the ADI
In addition to reducing economic activity and increasing unemployment, the biggest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI from January to June amounted to 630 597 dollars, which corresponds to a float of 87.74 percent compared to the 5,143 312 dollars in the same period of the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Authority for Economic Development) has a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In the light of the economic crisis, in July the State Government requested a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities.
Reactions
The first year of government, Mario López Valdé's inability to government was made clear to the representatives of entrepreneurship.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of the Processing Industry in Mexico), stated that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the various sectors, including the national government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very poor this year. It has to be worked hard to regain the lost terrain this year and in 2012 we have to make double efforts. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the well-coordinated government team have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events, such as the frost at the beginning of the year, made the country's economic development difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important impacts is a slow-down economy that is not moving enough to produce an economic dynamics that could produce an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will complete the year far below our expectations," he said.
Redefine Profession
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexico Business Association) in Sinaloa, said that the state had to be brought about more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme to redefine the country's economic vocation and line, because it is important to activate all material and human resources Sinaloas," he said.
There's a lot to do
The Chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that would lead to better government efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas in which it can be said that the government has acted more extensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
