The Court approved the transition to digital television in Mexico for 2015
The switch from analogue to digital signals has been one of the most important changes in the world in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional complaints filed by the Senate and the House of Deputies against the Presidential Decree, which require the transfer of analogues to digital signals from 2021 to 2015, due to the absence of eight votes necessary for the legal challenge.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, felt that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his responsibilities when he issued the Decree-Law with the details of the switch to terrestrial digital television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute raised by the Senate, since it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes, so that the court could decide on constitutionality or non-constitutionality. Thus, the law remains in force.
In the appeals project, which was drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed to declare the Legislative Decree unconstitutional as the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicación (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico) is responsible for the regulations relating to radio and television, which is why the Decree-Law would contradict the hierarchical principles and legal reservations.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the Decree-Law. Following the adoption of the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Decree-Law and ceased all activities to establish the digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the appeal lodged by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the debate on the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In his contribution, the Prime Minister said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the government should not regulate the measures to be taken by the public administration under general rules.
"I also do not believe that if this were done, the independence of the regulatory body would be affected." She also recalled that the central government is responsible for the planning of strategic policies, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, as it directs state affairs.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years around the world, and it results in better use of the radioelectric spectrum, an increased quality of the signal and more channels.
The postponement of the changeover, she said, was a delay in the exploitation of digitalisation, which was a decision in the public interest, which had not only technical aspects, "because it covers economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "required the action of the entire system, in accordance with the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of characteristics which put the Constitution in the hands of the central government."
It called to mind that many countries around the world had already implemented the digital transition, although they had highly specialised institutions.
It could not be concluded that the government intervened in the powers of Congress with the publication of the disputed decree, because the laws passed by the legislature would be respected," she assured.
The possibility of counting the ballots in Michoacán separately is considered.
According to the information provided by PREP, the difference between the first and second places in the election of the Governor is just under 27 percent, with 879 votes in total of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of the individual counting of the ballot is a reality in the elections in Michoacán this year, because according to the data issued by the Programa de Resultsados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between the first and second place in the governorial elections is just 27 percent, with 879 votes of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, pointed out that just last 9 November, the electorate had adopted a number of rules to harmonise local rules with the reforms of the states in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had neither adapted his political constitution nor his electoral law nor his law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by Congress, so that they had not entered into force during this electoral round. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the public prosecutor within the time limits provided for it with the argument or objection.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional complaint filed by the local legislature and judged the Ombudsman's vote on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and unlawful", since it did not have the right to "find" it or " veto it".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained in an interview about the possibility of individual counting of votes that, thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, there is now the possibility that the local electoral authority could count the ballot in part or in full.
Under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be counted in part.The results of the minutes do not match; the minutes on the counting and calculation of votes do not appear on file or are not in the possession of the chairman of the electoral committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
In addition, the total number of full ballot cards may be counted if there is a difference between the alleged winner and the one standing in the second place, which is equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of those candidates.
The total number of votes may also be counted if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate is equal to or less than one percent in the second place, provided that there is an explicit request from a representative of the party whose second candidate has become. In this case, the voting packages which have been partially counted would be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between the first and second place is almost 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
