Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation, led by the Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several Ministers and Entrepreneurs, will start their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss regional policy issues.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón. According to the Uruguayan President, this will be the highlight of his booked schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the Uruguayan community living in Mexico.
The meeting of both presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries", announced the Presidential Office of the South American country on its website.
According to local media, Mujica seeks the support of Calderón regarding the incident with France, when French head of government Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 Summit in Cannes.
In his discourse, Mr Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries which are still acting as tax havens, which was rejected by Uruguay and led to a question from his ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20, one of the world’s most powerful emerging and industrial countries since November. Since January this year, there has been an agreement on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation with the South American country.
In recent years, the Uruguayan Government has tried to speed up the concreteisation of agreements for the exchange of tax information in order to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).
Since 2004, there has been a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
