Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the aircraft accident in which the Secretary of Government Francisco Blake and another seven people were killed.
The Secretary of Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Secretariat für Kommunikation und Transport in Mexico) informed that the results of the investigation of the accident in which the Secretary of Government Francisco Blake Mora and another seven persons were killed indicate that the helicopter was rallied directly against the ground with its entire undamaged structure, without the pilot being able to initiate an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before the launch that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wing had contact with trees at 25 metres high, with the helicopter losing its hull seems to indicate that the helicopter had had several ground contacts."
He also stated that the helicopter was built for 19 passengers, which is why he met all the requirements for the transport of the staff.
In addition, he said that no helicopter parts were found in the investigations in the area where the machine had come down.
"In the search, no aircraft parts were found in other locations, which covered the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 passengers, which is why it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has a slope of 7 to 30 degrees.
At present, it is a priority to obtain the results of the studies as soon as possible, but they could take several months, perhaps even a year.
On the other hand, Gilberto López Meyer, Director-General of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretary of Aircraft and Relief Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter of the Estado Mayor Presidencial had flown at a flight speed and the plane had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of the impact."
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points that should be taken into account in the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with the flight standards, this was a flight according to the rules of the visual flight, which means that the crew must have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded appropriate weather conditions during the take-off. During the transit to the border area between Mexico City and the Mexico State, some deep-hanging clouds rose.
Selected routes:
It is possible that due to the clouds the team had chosen a lower area with a better view towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Impact site:
The impact coordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter are in line. Before the impact, there may not have been any loss of control over the aircraft or deviation from the flight route.
Dissemination of the remains of the aeroplane in a limited area:
The information available up to this time indicates that the helicopter had been impacted in a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of scattered aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter was impacted on the ground with its unharmed structure.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft offer at the site of the accident neither on fire nor on explosion.
The final results of the investigation indicate several ground contacts.
In the on-site investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9200 feet above sea level. The terrain is parched and has a slope of between seven and thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter is likely to have broken.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a minute search in an area that went beyond the enclosed area of the site of the accident, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, which reinforced the assumption that the undamaged aircraft structure was rallied against the ground.
MSS announces a research protocol to find the gene for obesity
The National Social Insurance Institute of Mexico is directing a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and young people, supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexico Social Insurance Institute) announced that it is leading a research project on the discovery of obesity genes in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth", with which the genetic markers are to be found in association with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unitad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department for Medical Research, Focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especiliades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, said that an interdisciplinary team, consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers, was established.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate course at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and at the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested people can come to the sports grounds of the IMSS in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and young people are carried out every Saturday starting at 8 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation began at the Cuahtémoc sports field (western Mexico State) and was continued since 8 October at the Nezahualcóyolt sports field (eastern México State).
If the goal is met by 500 to 600 investigators, the study will be continued on the Independencia sports field (in the south of the capital district) and completed on the one of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He stated that the aim of the study was to identify factors and the role of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors for Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the worldwide day of diabetes, he stated that three thousand children and young people aged six to 14 years should be filled in with the consent and supervision of their parents in questionnaires related to nutrition.
You will also be asked questions about their physical activity and their family history of disease to control risk factors that may result in diabetes or kidney failure.
He also stated that on Saturdays the investigators (weight, size, waist size), their blood pressure were controlled and blood levels such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors were determined (trying to identify genes related to obesity in childhood).
Cruz López stressed that this study would be carried out on the basis of health care professionals' concerns about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"Health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of obese girls by 47 percent. Excessive weight also increased dramatically," said the specialist of the IMSS.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico was different from that of other peoples.
He stated that one (e) Mexican (in) is an average of 65 percent of Indian-American, 30 percent of European and 5 percent of African descent, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity were inability to burn out the excess of energy (calories) taken from us, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that direct benefits for the investigators were found in a comprehensive study of children who would determine whether they had a degree of obesity or obesity.
It would even investigate the occurrence of dark skin folds in the neck and the inner arm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and pre-existing diabetes.
All information would be treated confidentially and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors. The doctors explain all the measurement results to the parents and suggest changes in the lifestyle that are appropriate for the prevention of diseases.
Cruz López explained that there were three basic factors responsible for overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, i.e. lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport, instead of walking short paths.
The high calorie intake, i.e., increased consumption of sugared drinks and carbohydrates (Tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) along with a high fat and protein intake as well as the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt prevented by UNAM
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM developed modified asphalts with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
Would it not be necessary to repair nearly 200 000 keyholes if the rainy season broke out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the valley of Mexico), Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warned and assured that if the laying and maintenance of the asphalt coating were appropriately damaged, the number of strokes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Slapholes from a technical point of view", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible developed modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, but which has greater mechanical resistance both at high and low temperatures.
Mr.era Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid the occurrence of pitfalls.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, a part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalt - and the other part a low - the so-called maltene. Together they give the road surface its characteristic elastic behaviour.
The calcareous behaviour of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very solid and almost solid at 50°C, while at very low temperatures it breaks down.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," explained the chemical engineer.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of flexible road surface consisting of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a layer of asphalt, which consists of small, asphalted and then fortified stones.
Every single stone of this layer of wear has been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he explained, "a final layer is laid out, the so-called bearing layer consisting of tiny stones, i.e., sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they need to produce friction.
This road surface receives and distributes the most forces, and the bearing layer also needs an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, above all the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes wet, water enters the layer and escapes only difficult again. This causes a softening of all layers of the pavement and consequently the appearance of percussion holes.
When a punch hole occurs," he said, "the layer is first worn off, while the layer of wear is only affected afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that would have to be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (Mexico's National Research System) stated that the vehicle load was another important cause for the occurrence of impact holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface always had to be proportionate to the vehicle load and it had to be ensured that this regulation was complied with in order to avoid frequent impact holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there were still a lot of research work to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, with which the keyholes could easily be repaired without the use of high temperatures.
