On Tuesday, the Austrian government in power of the great Social-Democratic/Christian Coalition decided to include a "Golden Budget Rule" in the Constitution to reduce public deficits and also to avoid possible degradation by rating agencies in the Austrian Top-Bonity (AAA).
It was the Social-Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who had announced this decision on the outcome of the Council of Ministers, although the public debt of Austria is 74.6%, far above the 60% criterion laid down by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the level of debt of the countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's ability to pay was not reduced to a blow from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros of interest each year," argued Michael Spindelegger, Vice Chancellor and Christian-Democrat Foreign Minister.
Austria also makes a request for the Brussels Eurozone Member States Summit of 26 October: The Heads of State and Government would then have demanded the inclusion of the reduction of public deficits by the end of 2012 and a return to the public balance of accounts in the Constitution or by the adoption of an equivalent law.
The measure taken by the Austrian Government is similar to the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to have incorporated such a "rule" into the Constitution.
By 2017, the structural budget deficit should decrease by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, while the structural budget deficit of the state should not exceed the 0.35% GDP ceiling from 2017 onwards, while the regional and local authorities should have balanced budgets.
The aim is to eliminate household debt under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Agreement in the 2020/21 horizon.
