Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the Baltic Sea seabed and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is intended to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to perform this event with brilliance and Gloria.
Over 500 invited guests, including four Heads of State and Government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level, on the Baltic Sea coast with orchestral sound and fine-tasting buffet.
German chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have symbolically turned together the load of the valve, which carries the Russian gas into the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year will be delivered to Western Europe through a first pipeline of 1,224 km long, connecting the St Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of total French consumption - will be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already let the possibility of building a third line begin on the track itself.
For Gazprom, the timely and point-to-point completion of this huge building seems like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The North-Stream pipeline will allow for direct gas delivery to Germany, while avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) on the road.
For this reason, these two countries lose some of their power: it is now more difficult for them to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most strongly engaged in the debate, was not shy away from comparing the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet Pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that, politically speaking, the subject is too sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply through its support for this Russian project.
This, however, at the expense of a decarbonisation of European energy, as the project has made a breakthrough between Western and Eastern Europeans.
Russia has completed its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, western countries, which have strong gas consumption and whose gas deposits tend to decline in just under five years.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," said François Fillon at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the large gas contracts are also politically and economically important.
All of this explains the wide smile of the numerous Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The submerged line consists of steel with concrete coating to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at about 200 m depth.
Mining fields dating from the Second World War had to be eliminated during their construction.
"Some hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed carefully," said Jens Müller, spokesperson of Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect fauna and flora.
The line is a long hose made of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which is interrupted by nothing over the entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off Sweden's coast, but the project managers have declined because the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state company settle in a permanent manner at the height of their coasts.
"In the event of a breakdown, we close the gas flow in less than a minute," Jens Müller explained.
So in the event of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered by the constructors to be less likely, as the welding seams were estimated to be resistant to one leak per 100,000 years.
The state control of the gas pipeline is ensured by an underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes by a seaship, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, measures a meter in diameter, is introduced into the inside of the pipe and moved through the gas pressure.
After three complete days of transit through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on possible deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to function for fifty years without having to undergo even the smallest repair.
The gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have joined forces to achieve this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
In addition, the German companies E. ON and BASF (each 15.5%), as well as the Dutch gas union and the French company group GDF Suez (each 9%) are affiliated here.
These five companies have formed a group of companies called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug in Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire gas transport capacity to this company, on a renewable 20-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real volume of gas transported will fall," Jens Müller explained.
The financing of the gas pipeline was secured to 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amount was 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are certain to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline emerges on a sandy, forested coastline at Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5-metre-high valves form the gas outlet.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is passed on to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been delivered with a million cubic metres of Russian gas per hour.
With full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic metres per hour and 6 million in 2012.
