The Italian company Modo Modo, which has its headquarters in Milan, decided at the time to place on the market a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, at the time specialist consultant of the company, is commissioned to launch the new product on the market.
The notebook was inspired by an old-fashioned production technique called Mole Skin (Mole Skin) which describes a cotton varnish used for coverings of upholstery benches, for example.
This type of notebook was very much in demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object, which until the 20th century was regarded as an icon of avant-garde artists," explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand-responsible at Modo Modo.
Success is coming.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales rose by 26% and established themselves with a sales volume of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported in 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a phantom image of the buyers, as the notebook inspires businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultivated and open-minded customers.
The small, Italian company, which in its beginnings numbered 12 employees, employs over 100 employees today and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan, the other in New York.
The company distributes its notebooks in bookstores, on web portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques of city centers and understands how to enforce its identity.
"We have followed the zeitgeist and its new need for writing, which exists despite the upswing of the e-mails," said Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the company Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exposure called "Detour" in which architects and artists issued their own notebooks.
In August, on the occasion of the film festival in Locarno, the company also launched a cover with leopard patterns.
Moleskine benefited from his success and this cultural zeitgeist and understood to diversify his products: bags, appointment calendar, fillers, computer shells... The brand has the entire range of articles.
A success that engenders the plan: In autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought up by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today's Syntegra Capital, and thus opened a new chapter in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today the "15th week of work for disabled people" begins.
Despite a determined public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is always twice as high as the average average: 19% against 9% of the total population.
Discouraging?
"No, so emphasizes Éric Blanchet, Director-General of the Adapt Association, which is organising the "week of work for the disabled."
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not double, but tripled."
"Nevertheless, much remains to be done."
However, it must be said that many obstacles remain for disabled people before they get a job.
Older people are more common: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low qualification level: 80% of them do not have a diploma and there are only 10,000 disabled people among the 2.3 million students with a higher degree.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% for the disabled compared with 38% for the total.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to re-enter work and that form the "core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, Director-General of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992, which helps companies to recruit disabled workers.
So much for the actual brakes.
Keep the unspoken, the spiritual attitudes, which, though certain, but still continue slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS Entreprendre for the magazine La Cité indicated that the managers surveyed "have a weak level of knowledge about the disabled", which was "overrepresented" by people in wheelchairs, mental or intellectually impaired persons.
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go in order to achieve the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, which was laid down in a 1987 law.
These latter figures from 2008 refer to a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now at 3%," reports Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Proof: The number of "fees paid" establishments has decreased, as has the sum of the sums paid up between 2007 and 2011, from 59.000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Law, which provides for increases in contributions, created strong pressure on companies," said Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also expresses a real awareness, especially of the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of establishments employ disabled workers between 20 and 49, while enterprises with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
